<subSubSection pageId="12" pageNumber="61" type="comments">
<paragraph pageId="12" pageNumber="61">Comments.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="12" pageNumber="61">
Apparently closely related to 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Anthrax" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Anthrax irroratus" order="Diptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="61" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="irroratus">Anthrax irroratus</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Anthrax" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Anthrax oedipus" order="Diptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="61" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="oedipus">Anthrax oedipus</taxonomicName>
has a narrow distribution in the Nearctic region but is widely distributed in all South America. In the USA it has been collected only in two southern states, while it occurs in most of the northern states of Mexico and one central state (Morelos); it may be present in most areas from Texas to Argentina.
</paragraph>
